CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed Case Noted The request to break the ice is denied. According to the Massachusetts Audubon Society  ducks have adapted to this climate and will move to find open water if they need to. Ponds in this region have frozen each winter for millennia and ducks have survived here. Ducks are primarily herbivores and rarely eat fish. We have seen this happen seasonally for many years.  According to Audoban Society  the ducks will be fine.  If you have any questions  please contact us on the Parkline at 617-635-7275. Thank you.

CLOSURE_REASON: Case Closed. Closed date : 2016-08-19 09:01:45.217 Case Resolved National Grid is installing a new main on your street. The city highly encourages this type of work. It will eliminate possible future emergency leak repairs.     The city acknowledges that the construction will cause an inconvenience to the residents.    However in the long run the construction is well worth it.     Having a street dug up for emergency repairs soon after paving is frustrating for all. With the new gas main installed  the city can feel extremely comfortable that no embarrassing street cuts will happen if it determines to pave your street in the future.     The CIU inspector states the contractor uses steel plates at the end of each work day so traffic can safely pass by.    The inspector will monitor the worksite to ensure full compliance with the city's rules.     The city apologizes for the inconvenience this necessary work has caused.    Sincerely      Mark Cardarelli  Supervisor of Utility Coordination and Compliance  Boston Public Works Department  617-635-4951 Office
SUBJECT: Public Works Department
Location: INTERSECTION of Hull St & Commercial St  Boston  MA
